Description.val: The EA-18G is replacing the EA-6B aircraft. The EA-18G has the capability to operate autonomously or as a major node in a network centric operation. The performance of the aircraft is compatible with the primary strike/fighter aircraft inventory, allowing it to be fully integrated into specific strike packages. It also has the capacity to provide broad area coverage for extended periods of time to support numerous strikes or other air operations in a federated context.  The EA-18G is a scalable, flexible solution facilitating "Task Organized" force structures. Task organized force structures employ adequate forces to accomplish a specific task while maintaining operational and personnel tempo at acceptable levels. The EA-18G is designed to perform a range of Electronic Warfare/Electronic Attack functions either simultaneously or independently.  EA-18G man in the loop operation and advanced information display system allow real time assessment of the tactical situation and the appropriate response executed in accordance with the rules of engagement.The EA-18G's electronic attack upgrades meet or exceed EA-6B Airborne (with ALQ-218, ALQ-99, USQ-113) Electronic Attack (AEA) capability to detect, identify, locate and suppress hostile emitters; provide enhanced connectivity to National, Theater and strike assets; and provide organic precision emitter targeting for employment of onboard suppression weapons (HARM) to fulfill operational requirements.

Justification.val:
Funding is requested to procure 21 EA-18G aircraft in FY14.  The Navy will execute a single-year procurement contract line item on the existing MYP III contract vehicle for this procurement.

Since the EA-18G is a modified F/A-18F, some support costs are common and more efficiently executed out of one budget line. These common costs are budgeted in the F/A-18 E/F budget line. 
 
The FY14 funding request is part of an on-going Total Ownership Cost (TOC) initiative that provided funding for EA-18G I-level maintenance.  The FY15 funding will be used for EA-18G Depot Standup.  This effort establishes depot capability for repair of the Airborne Electronic Attack system to include ALQ-218, ALQ-227, Interference Cancellation System (INCANS), and Electronic Attack Unit (EAU).  This facilitates organic test and repair for Weapon Replaceable Assemblies (WRAs) and Shop Replaceable Assemblies (SRAs). This investment has reduced Airborne Electronic Attack (AEA) system life cycle costs by $1B over the life of the program.

Name.@footnote: Airframe/CFE:  The increase to the FY14 Airframe/CFE cost element can be attributed to the following: (1) Single Year vs. Multi-year Pricing.  FY14 is based on a Single Year Procurement (SYP) scenario vice the Multi Year Procurement (MYP) scenario in FY13.   (2) Quantity Reduction.  The FY13 procurement of 12 EA-18G aircraft was part of an overall procurement of 38 aircraft (includes 26 F/A-18E/F aircraft).  The FY14 procurement of 21 EA-18G aircraft is well below the minimum sustaining production rate of 24 aircraft.  Fixed costs are amortized against the quantities of aircraft procured in FY14; the lower quantity drives a higher fixed cost assigned to each aircraft.  Fixed costs include sustaining engineering, supplier management and other labor costs that are not quantity dependent or proportional to the aircraft quantity and overhead costs. (3) The FY14 procurement includes the funding necessary to fully fund the FY14 EA-18G aircraft. There is no Advance Procurement funding for the additional EA-18G aircraft.

FiscalYear.@footnote: Breaks in deliveries are accomodated by F/A-18 E/F production deliveries.

Name.@footnote: CFE Electronics: Airframe (line 1) and CFE (line 2) are combined as one negotiated average unit price under MYPIII. The negotiated distribution of the unit cost dollar amount between Budget Lines 1 and 2 varies annually for the MYPIII period. This variance in percentage contributes to the differences in unit cost. The FY14 unit cost was reduced due to recent Foreign Military Sales (FMS)/Royal Australian Air Firce (RAAF) procurement of 16 Airborne Electronic Attack(AEA) Kits.
GFE Electronics: The increase to the the FY14 GFE Electronics cost element is attributable to OSD inflation, economic order quantity increased and Naval Inventory Control Point (NAVICP) prices.

Engines/Engines Accessories: The FY14 Engines/Engines Accessories cost element unit cost was reduced due to current negotiated contract and Cost and Software Data Reporting (CSDR) based learning curve projections for engines and devices.
GFE: The increase to the the FY14 GFE cost element is attributable to OSD inflation, economic order quantity increased and Naval Inventory Control Point (NAVICP) prices.

Rec Flyaway ECO: Recurring Flyaway ECO funding is a calculation based on 2% of the Airframe and CFE cost elements.  The increase in procurement quantities drove the increase to the Airframe and CFE cost elements which increased the ECO funding level.  The FY13 and FY14 ECO calculations have remained consistent at 2%; the FY14 increase to the cost element is attributable to the increase in quantity.
Non-Recurring Cost: FY14 funding is for the AEA kit production line shutdown.

Avionics PGSE: The increase in the FY13 cost element is due to the procurement of additional 26 EA-18G expeditionary aircraft that were added as part of the FY2011 President's Budget. The funding was added for the additional cost of the Expeditionary Logistic Units (ELUs) needed to support the deployed aircraft. The increase in the FY14 cost element is due to the additional 21 EA-18G expeditionary aircraft in FY14 and two ELUs (1 ELU in FY14 and 1 ELU in FY15) that were added as part of the FY2014 President's Budget and part of an on-going Total Ownership Cost (TOC) initiative that provided funding for EA-18G I-level maintenance. This effort establishes depot capability for repair of the Airborne Electronic Attack system to include ALQ-218, ALQ-227, Interference Cancellation System (INCANS), and Electronic Attack Unit (EAU).  This facilitates organic test and repair for Weapon Replaceable Assemblies (WRAs) and Shop Replaceable Assemblies (SRAs). This investment has reduced Airborne Electronic Attack (AEA) system life cycle costs by $1B over the life of the program.

Production Engineering Support (PES):  Per OSD direction, the F/A-18E/F and EA-18G APN-1 budgets were split during the OSD-05 budget development (October 2003) and as directed, all F/A-18E/F and EA-18G common support costs have been budgeted in the F/A-18E/F APN-1 budget.  There are no FY14 F/A-18E/F procurements programmed; the increase to the EA-18G Production Engineering and Other ILS cost elements reflect the full funding of all EA-18G costs necessary to support delivery of the programmed procurements.

Integrated Logistics Support (ILS): Per OSD direction, the F/A-18E/F and EA-18G APN-1 budgets were split during the OSD-05 budget development (October 2003) and as directed, all F/A-18E/F and EA-18G common support costs have been budgeted in the F/A-18E/F APN-1 budget.  There are no FY14 F/A-18E/F procurements programmed; the increase to the EA-18G Production Engineering and Other ILS cost elements reflect the full funding of all EA-18G costs necessary to support delivery of the programmed procurements.
